	abstract = {The pH of grape juice or wine is a the major quality factor. Research has demonstrated that rootstocks can affect grape juice pH by changing grape juice K+ concentration. Field and glasshouse studies indicated that this effect of rootstocks on scion grape juice pH and K+ levels originate from different K+ uptake rates of rootstock varieties. At least with the varieties tested, these genotypic differences in K+ uptake only occurred at high levels of K+ supply, and not at low levels of K+ supply. This indicates that as in the roots of most other plant species. a dual K+ uptake mechanism exists in roots of grapevines, and that only the mechanism operational at high K+ levels is different in the rootstock varieties studied. It therefore appears feasible to breed rootstock varieties, which combine high K+ efficiency at low K+ supply with restricted K+ uptake at high supply. This model is currently being verified under German conditions on a range of rootstock varieties.},
