	abstract = {The problem of feral and stray cat predation is an old one and the effects are evident, however, the consequences are highly underestimated. Studies that analyze these effects are limited and offer no clear description. It is essential to provide a detailed review regarding cat predation and outline the dangers and possible solutions. Felines are highly adaptable and very effective predators. Feral cats have played part in driving countless bird and mammal species to extinction. Cat predation is especially worrying on small islands as potential prey may lack evolved defensive mechanisms to avoid predators. As soon as an invasive species is first introduced to the new area they begin an exponential reproduction and thus, disperse quickly in a new ecosystem. Upon the first successful introduction, invasive species either occupy an available niche or outcompete a previous inhabitant of the niche. Domestic cats proved to be successful in this regard as they managed to reproduce, disperse and outcompete other species in no time. On top of that, feral and stray cats carry diseases that may further decline wildlife populations. T. gondii antibodies were found in species such as mouflon, red deer, fallow deer, roe deer and wild boar. This is worrying as game meat consumption around the world has increased over the last decades and thus Toxoplasmosis has become a real threat for humans as well. Other diseases carried and transmitted by feral and stray cats include rabies, feline leukemia and cat scratch. Due to the fact that cats have been closely associated with humans for centuries, discussing the methods of cat control is controversial. There are two main methods talked about among the public – Trap Neuter Release (TNR) and catch – remove. TNR is favored by many animal welfare organizations since it is believed to gradually decrease cat population while at the same time relieve cats of mating and parenting stress. Conservationists, on the other hand, argue in favor of eradication methods as it is believed to be the only fast and effective solution. However, despite the disagreement, both sides agree that it is crucial that cats are kept indoors and are equipped with bell collars. This thesis provides a summary of the problem, the management and the solutions developed to reduce feral and stray cats in order to mitigate the problems they have caused.},
	author = {Kalandarishvili, Alexandra},
	month = sep,
	year = {2019},
	doi = {10.13140/RG.2.2.13259.75040},
	file = {Full Text PDF:/Users/christophe_rouleau-desrochers/Zotero/storage/2U3AWBVX/Kalandarishvili - 2019 - THE EFFECT OF STRAY AND FERAL CATS ON WILDLIFE BAS.pdf:application/pdf},
